{
  "texts": [
    "On the other hand, some events considered stressful, such as getting married or raising children [10], may form new social connections that alter health behaviors in a positive way [11].",
    "Research on breast cancer adherence shows that supportive social networks can encourage cancer screening [12].",
    "Thus, stressful life events, from the perspective of the health belief model [13], can act as both facilitators of screening (e.g., when they form new social connections, such as in the case of marriage or childbirth) or as barriers (e.g., when they negatively impact mental health or when social connections break down).Furthermore, life events, such as getting married, have differential effects depending on a set of individual circumstances and personality factors [14].",
    "Marriage has been long considered a positive factor in well-being and preventive health behavior [15].",
    "While the literature generally supports the notion that marriage is associated with improved well-being, research has shown that marital satisfaction can vary between spouses, with husbands' satisfaction often being more dependent on the specific content of the relationship, while wives' satisfaction is influenced by both the quality of the marriage and their overall well-being [16].There is also significant variability in life events commonly perceived as negative or adverse."
  ]
}